<script type="text/javascript">
  ars.ARTICLE = {"url":"http:\/\/arstechnica.com\/business\/2014\/03\/heres-how-to-spend-your-hard-earned-arscoins\/","short_url":"http:\/\/ars.to\/1mCGdSH","title":"Here\u2019s how to spend your hard-earned Arscoins","author":335607,"id":400667,"topic":1236795,"promoted":[26368981],"single_page":false,"comments":211,"fullwidth":false};
</script>

<article class="standalone comments-open">
	<header>
		<h1 class="heading">Here’s how to spend your hard-earned Arscoins</h1>
		<h2 class="standalone-deck">Send coins to a friend or buy a silly hat for the Ars Technica forums.</h2>
		<div class="post-meta">
        <p class="byline">
  by     <a href="http://arstechnica.com/author/cyrus-farivar/" rel="author">Cyrus Farivar</a>
  -    <span class="date" data-time="1394024502">Mar 5, 2014 1:01 pm UTC</span>
  </p>

			<div class="corner-info">
				<ul class="tags subheading">
        					<li><a href="/discipline/finance-business-3">Finance</a></li>
        					<li><a href="/discipline/media-innovation">Media Innovation</a></li>
        				</ul>
          <a title="113 posters participating" class="comment-count" href="http://arstechnica.com/business/2014/03/heres-how-to-spend-your-hard-earned-arscoins/?comments=1"><span>211</span></a>

			</div>
		</div>
	</header>
	<section id="article-guts">
		<div class="article-content clearfix">
    
<figure class="intro-image image center full-width" style="width:640px">
      <img src="http://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/arsstore-640x478.jpg" width="640" height="478">
  
    <figcaption class="caption">
			<div class="caption-text">The first store to accept Arscoins!</div>
	
			<div class="caption-credit">
							<a rel="nofollow" href="https://coins.arstechnica.com/store">Ars Technica</a>
				</div>
	  </figcaption>
  </figure>
 <div class="article-intro">The Arscoin project is for those who want to experiment with digital currencies—and buy some fun hats and colored usernames along the way. In other words, it is for <b>educational use only</b>; we have centralized the system in order to prevent it from developing into a real-money economy. </div><!-- cache miss -->
<aside class="related-stories">
  <h2 class="subheading notched">Arscoin</h2>
	<ul>
	    <li><a href="http://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2014/03/the-arscoin-rollout-through-the-eyes-of-the-server-administrators/">The Arscoin rollout, through the eyes of the server administrators</a></li>
      <li><a href="http://arstechnica.com/business/2014/03/tell-us-what-crazy-hardware-have-you-thrown-at-mining-arscoin/">Tell us: What crazy hardware have you thrown at mining Arscoin?</a></li>
      <li><a href="http://arstechnica.com/business/2014/03/digging-for-cryptocurrency-the-newbies-guide-to-mining-altcoins/">Digging for cryptocurrency: The newbie’s guide to mining altcoins</a></li>
    </ul>
  <span class="read-more"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/series/arscoin-2/">View all&hellip;</a></span>
</aside>
 <p>So now you know about <a href="http://arstechnica.com/business/2014/03/behold-arscoin-our-own-custom-cryptocurrency/">Arscoins</a>; maybe you've managed to <a href="http://arstechnica.com/business/2014/03/digging-for-cryptocurrency-the-newbies-guide-to-mining-altcoins/">mine some for yourself</a>. Now what? What are they good for?</p>
<p>We’re glad you asked. For now, there are two main ways that you can transact your Arscoins: send them to another Arscoin user or use them to buy digital goods on Ars Technica.</p>
<p>Using your Arscoin miner and online wallet app, you can send Arscoins in any denomination you like to any other Arscoin user with ease—you can just as easily send 1,000 ARS as you can 0.0001 ARS.</p>
<figure class="image center" style="width:597px"><img src="http://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/online.wallet.jpg" width="597" height="619"><figcaption class="caption"><div class="caption-text">Cyrus Farivar's online Arscoin wallet, as of February 28, 2014.</div> <div class="caption-credit">Cyrus Farivar</div></figcaption></figure>
<p>Here’s how to do it:</p>
<p><strong>Step 1</strong>: Ask for your friend’s Arscoin address. It will be a long string of numbers and letters (for example, mine is <code>1Kh2VN6E9pYW5UWWYWrDGUvwr4syQbJ7Ja</code>). Your friend can find his or her address by checking under the “Wallet” tab in the Arscoin online app.</p>
<p>Keep in mind that every Arscoin transaction (<a href="http://blockchain.info/tx/17336399fee7d991df974ff876374b3f675084ebbc146736238a6a85d5a35edc">like every Bitcoin transaction</a>) is pseudonymous, so if your wallet number is public and is affiliated with your name, it’s quite likely that others could follow your transactions.</p>
<p><strong>Step 2</strong>: In the “Send to Arscoin address” field, copy and paste your friend’s wallet address and type in the amount. Click send. That’s it!</p>
<p>You’ll know the money has cleared when your balance adjusts, or when it shows up under the “Overview” tab.</p>
<p>If you prefer to spend your Arscoins on something slightly less-than-practical, you might try our online store, where you can buy all kinds of digital hats—or turn your Ars username into gold!</p>
<p>To spend your coins, follow these steps:</p>
<p><strong>Step 1</strong>: Go to the <a href="https://coins.arstechnica.com/store">Arscoin Store page</a> and choose your item.</p>
<p><strong>Step 2</strong>: Copy and paste the Arscoin wallet address listed there back into the online wallet app. Send the amount listed to the address you’ve just pasted.</p>
<p><strong>Step 3</strong>: Refresh that page to see when your order has been fulfilled.</p>
<p><strong>Step 4</strong>: Taunt your friends with your newfound ridiculous virtual headgear.</p>
    		</div>
    <div class="article-expander">
      <p><a href="http://arstechnica.com/business/2014/03/heres-how-to-spend-your-hard-earned-arscoins/">Expand full story</a></p>
    </div>
			</section>

  
