    <span class="author" data-post-author="Deus Casus"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=31314&amp;sid=6593d84e665d882e0a4339149dd9b70e">Deus Casus</a></span><span class="rank">Ars Praefectus</span>
      <aside class="icons">
        
        <a href="http://arstechnica.com/business/2014/03/heres-how-to-spend-your-hard-earned-arscoins/?comments=1&post=26368713#comment-26368713" title="2014-03-05T09:20:00-06:00" class="timeago datetime">Wed Mar 05, 2014 9:20 am</a>
        
        <span class="hidden-icon-start"></span>
        
      </aside>
    </header>
    <div class="body">
      <div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=26368493#p26368493" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">OmniWrench</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=26368271#p26368271" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">Old_Fogie_Late_Bloomer</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=26367807#p26367807" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">leedo</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=26367743#p26367743" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">aruisdante</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=26367721#p26367721" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">leedo</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Does this pope hate look like a joke?!</div><br /><br />Well, a little, since it doesn't actually fully render, it's cut off by the left margin of the page <img src="//cdn.arstechnica.net/civis/images/smilies/wink.png" alt=";)" title="Wink" /><br /><br />But there is most definitely a store behind that link, that's for sure.</div><br />What browser and OS are you using? I'm not seeing any clipping in my testing so far. Thanks!</div><br />Broken for me on Win 7, IE8 (not my choice to use the latter).<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=26368101#p26368101" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">MorseCode</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I was considering stopping reading Ars and it looks like now’s a good time.</div><br />Why are people getting their knickers in a twist over this?  How does this humorous little exercise cheapen the value of Ars's other work?</div><br /><br />My knickers aren't in a twist at all, but it seems awfully odd to me that this much effort (developing a digital currency and a web storefront and associated front page infrastructure, ...) would be put into just &quot;a humorours little excercise&quot;. <br /><br />As is, sure it's a harmless distraction, but I'm reminded (as I just did my taxes), of the tax program I use. A few years ago it was a great program that did my taxes in a way that suited me, great, so I use it every year. Over they years they've clearly decided that they want to generate more income from making a tax program, so they began adding &quot;click here to sign up for XZY!&quot; to some sections. This year I was literally clicking &quot;no, I don't want that either, let me get to the next form&quot; every 3-4 clicks. They even helpfully move the location of the &quot;no&quot; button on the different up-sells so you can't mindlessly &quot;no, no, no&quot; everything. It's very considerate of them, I might miss the chance to give them more money otherwise. The core software is still as good as it was years ago, but the experience is so soured by the constant relentless up-sell that I will almost certainly be using something else next year. <br /><br />The fear is, in a few months we're going to be getting little arscoin tie-ins in more and more articles, and more and more stuff in the store, and then maybe some stuff you'd actually want in the store, or maybe some things about the website become annoying, but this arscoin stuff, that'll fix it! and then maybe there's some people who  would want this new stuff, but don't want to bother mining right, so maybe we'll tie the arscoin stuff into something else, something more material and valuable, and boy, have we mentioned how great this arscoin stuff is? Look at all these benefits! You want to sign up, right?<br /><br />Sure, it probably won't happen, but again, it seems odd to put this much effort into a silly experiment with hats and nothing else... but honestly, this is a website, it's currently a great one, but if they muck things up people who care will go elsewhere. I hear there are websites like, all over the place! Ars is a buisness, they need to make money, I don't dispute or mind that in the least, but if their attempts to make more money annoy me too much and begin distracting from the good stuff, I'll just stop visiting.<br /><br />Again, I'm not personally upset over this, and I'm not leaving, I can't even believe I spent a few minutes typing a reply to this silliness to be honest... but it definitely &quot;smells&quot; like a step in a direction that might have me visiting less. Who knows, and honestly, who cares at this point.</div><br /><br /><br />See I see it as an excuse to research creating new alt coins since that seems to be a big thing now.  The hats and what not are just a fun outcome of that.  The original article was very informative about how to go and set up an altcoin and some of the more complex software / ideas behind that.  I'll probably spin up a miner on my server later when I'm home but not sure if I'll buy anything.
      
    </div>
